          "final_answer_tail": ": \"high\", \"est_confidence\": 0.75}\n{\"id\": \"C\", \"title\": \"Semi-synthetic: Chemical Oxidation of Amorphadiene\", \"route\": \"semi-synthetic\", \"host\": null, \"summary\": \"Produce amorphadiene via yeast fermentation, followed by chemical oxidation using metal catalysts to reach artemisinic acid.\", \"est_difficulty\": \"medium\", \"est_confidence\": 0.85}\n</plan>\n\nPick an approach and I'll produce the full design.",
          "final_answer_full": "\nthought\n<channel|>To engineer *Saccharomyces cerevisiae* for artemisinic acid production, you must redirect the native mevalonate (MVA) pathway toward the production of farnesyl pyrophosphate (FPP) and then introduce a heterologous sesquiterpene pathway from *Artemisia annua*.\n\nThe engineering strategy involves three main modules: increasing precursor supply (FPP), expressing the sesquiterpene synthase to form the scaffold, and implementing a cytochrome P450 system for oxidative tailoring.\n\n### Proposed Engineering Plan\n\n<plan>\n{\"id\": \"A\", \"title\": \"Microbial: Heterologous Sesquiterpene Pathway in Yeast\", \"route\": \"microbial\", \"host\": \"scerevisiae\", \"summary\": \"Overexpress MVA pathway genes (ERG20, ERG13) and introduce Amorpha-4,11-diene synthase (ADS) and CYP71AV1/CPR system.\", \"est_difficulty\": \"high\", \"est_confidence\": 0.95}\n{\"id\": \"B\", \"title\": \"Enzymatic: Cell-Free Multi-Enzyme Cascade\", \"route\": \"enzymatic\", \"host\": null, \"summary\": \"Utilize purified ADS, CYP71AV1, and CPR in a controlled bioreactor using FPP as the starting substrate.\", \"est_difficulty\": \"high\", \"est_confidence\": 0.75}\n{\"id\": \"C\", \"title\": \"Semi-synthetic: Chemical Oxidation of Amorphadiene\", \"route\": \"semi-synthetic\", \"host\": null, \"summary\": \"Produce amorphadiene via yeast fermentation, followed by chemical oxidation using metal catalysts to reach artemisinic acid.\", \"est_difficulty\": \"medium\", \"est_confidence\": 0.85}\n</plan>\n\nPick an approach and I'll produce the full design.",
